segments.text: First, Dr. Burns, tell us something about your early life, including the names of your parents, the dates of their birth and death, the place of their birth, the place and date of your birth, and the schools you attended before entering Texas A&M.
I was born in DeWitt County, Quirrell.
Lived out in the country a few miles from Quirrell.
My father was Lewis L. Burns.
He died in February 1928, and he was 76 years old and nine months.
That would make his birthday.
My mother was Anna Wright and this was my father's second wife.
His first wife died when she was about 30 or 35 years old.
My mother had
two children.
I have a sister eight years older than I.
And my mother died in 1856, lacked just a few months of being 90 years old.
When you said 1856, you meant 1956.
I beg your pardon, 1956.
I don't recall her
exact date of birth, year.
I was born on October 16, 1901.
Were you born in DeWitt County?
In DeWitt County.
And do you remember where your parents were born?
My father was born in DeWitt County.
My mother was
point in DeWitt County.
Did you go to school in Cuero or did you have a rural school?
No, I went to school in Cuero.
Rode to Horsback.
How many miles?
Oh, about three and a half or four.
I rode in a buggy and through the fourth grade with my sister and then she finished high school in 1912.
And I finished in 1919.
I rode a horseback the remaining years.
Was that, what, 11 years in the high school, or did you have 12?
Eleven years.
Okay.
What factors were involved in your choice of Texas A&M as a school?
Perhaps my father's love for it.
He used to come to these...
Farmers Congress, as they called them then.
Oh, perhaps not every year, but frequently.
And from the time I could talk or walk, I think I was destined to come to A&M.
How did you choose animal husbandry as your major?
I didn't choose it at first.
My father asked me on the way to the train, and I came up here as a freshman in September 1919, what course I was going to take.
I said, well, I think I'll take electrical engineering.
And I did for one semester.
Realized that I was interested
mainly in math.
Math was my favorite subject in high school.
And I was never interested in the practical applications of electrical engineering.
I realized I'd probably end up teaching algebra and teaching was just a jumping off place as far as I was concerned.
I wasn't interested and so I wrote to my father for permission to
Changed courses and being a miner at that time.
And took animal husbandry.
Finished in 1923.
Why did you choose animal husbandry?
That's kind of far removed from math.
I guess because I was born on a farm and ranch.
And that had been my life up until then.
Had you ever come to the campus with your father when he attended any of the congresses?
No.
So you had no firsthand knowledge of the area when you arrived?
No.
What were your first reactions to the school and to the community when you did get here?
Well, I guess with most freshmen it was entirely new life.
It was a big change for me.
But I guess they agreed with me and I picked up weight and grew a little bit.
Were there any people to meet the train when you arrived?
Any upperclassmen?
Well, some freshmen were put off the train at Navasota.
How I escaped, I don't know.
Some were taken off, got off at Hempstead.
at Hempstead, some Navasota, and some Welborn.
And how I managed to get to College Station, I don't know.
You say they were taken off with this by upperclassmen?
Yes.
I've been told that at one point there were people who met the train to try to recruit you for a particular military unit and thereby a dormitory.
No, not in my case.
And I've also been told that there were people who met the train to sell freshman tickets to take a shower.
I didn't have that experience.
You didn't have that experience, okay.
I'm not sure how widespread or how long that may have lasted, how widespread that may have been or how long it may have lasted.
What dormitory were you assigned to then as a freshman?
Mitchell Hall, and I was in the signal corps.
Did you have a choice in that?
Yes, I chose it, and when I switched to animal husbandry,
My roommate did the same thing, so we transferred to Company I infantry.
Was that because of your change of major?
Oh yes, you had to be an electrical engineering major to be in signal corps.
I see.
Then did you get a choice into which infantry company you transferred, or did they just assign you to one that had an opening?
I don't recall, but there were several students from my hometown in Company I.
Perhaps that was a factor in the choice.
Then when you switched to Company I Infantry, what dorm did you go to?
Bazell Hall.
And that was what, second half of your freshman year?
Yes.
Well, having been in those two relatively new dorms, you missed out on all the good things like carrying water and wood and so forth for the upper class.
Yes, that was Austin Pfeiffer.
Ross.
Ross Foster, I believe.
Yes.
Wow.
Did you...
What kinds of things did you have to do for upperclassmen in the newer dorms?
Oh, I don't recall.
Making up beds, sweeping out, and that's about all I recall.
Running errands.
Running errands, such as?
Well, some were foolish, and to carry things from Bazell Hall, say, down to Milner or Leggett, the other end of the campus, which wasn't very far.
But if you had to do it several times, it probably seemed far.
What other dormitories did you live in?
During the sophomore year, I switched to the Air Service, the old Air Service, and quite a few in company.
I went to the Cavalry when it was organized, and some went to
the air service and we were assigned a room in Ross Hall.
So then the air service and the cavalry were created during your sophomore year or at the beginning of it?
The air service was.
But the cavalry was earlier than that.
I think so.
I believe
in the fall of 1920, if I'm not mistaken.
I'm not sure.
So then your sophomore year, you lived in Ross.
The latter part, yes.
The latter part.
Okay.
Oh, so then the switch to the air service was not made in the fall of the supplement.
May I make a correction there?
We made our choice in the spring of 21, but we actually, my roommates were juniors.
And we roomed in Ross Hall during my junior year, not sophomore year.
Not sophomore year.
Okay, do you remember where it was in your sophomore year?
In Bazell Hall.
In Bazell Hall.
They dissolved Company I, and we were in Company H, I believe.
I'm not positive.
Okay.
Where were you then as a senior?
in Foster Hall.
So you had two of the old ones during that time.
How was the life in the dormitory?
Was it pretty crowded?
How many roommates did you have?
As a freshman in the Mitchell Hall, there were three of us.
Two of us were freshmen, one sophomore.
wasn't too good an arrangement for the two freshmen.
Convenient for the sophomore.
For the fish.
And in Vazell Hall, as a freshman, there were only two of us.
Both fish?
Both of us were fish.
In the sophomore year, three of us sophomores roomed together.
In the junior year in Ross Hall, three of us roomed together in triple-deckers, triple-deck beds.
And then as a senior, I roomed in Foster Hall.
We were the overflow of the Air Service, the remaining most of the unit.
were housed in Pfeiffer.
So Air Service had all old dormitories.

But do I understand it correctly that there was an annual almost musical dormitories that the various company's military units shifted from one dormitory to another each year so that the same company didn't have the same old dormitory each year?
Or do you recall?
Not that I recall.
Someone had indicated to me that he understood this as the way it was.
It might have been true, but I don't recall.
Of course, it may have changed at times, too.
They might have.
Because the infantry occupied Brazil and Goodwin for years.
You mentioned your triple-decker beds.
Did the college make them triple-decker, or did the students do that?
We had the metal for a double-decker, but we had to improvise on making the third one, stocking the third one on top of the other two.
How did you decide who got which of the levels?
We drew straws.
Yes, that's as fair a way as any, isn't it?
Odd man out, or we drew for it.
I imagine depending upon the season of the year, one level would certainly be more desirable than the other, would it not?
I don't know.
I happen to be the middle.
draw the middle ducker both years, so I don't know.
Probably got a little warm on the top one.
Which bottom one might be a little cool in the wintertime.
That's right.
And it might be the most desirable one in the summer, in the warmer weather though.
Yes.
And the top one I imagine would be hot always, summer or winter, up near the ceiling.
You mentioned earlier that during your freshman year you gained some weight.
This would indicate that the food in the mess hall was probably wholesome.
Well, sometimes you didn't get all the dessert.
You may not have had good pies, you just had to look at them.
But we got plenty of prunes.
In fact, the sophomores saved the prunes for the fish, for prune races.
And we got a little box of sun-made raisins, one every day.
And the students would frequently, on picture show nights, get the old, what they call the air dome, the open, located just about where the all-face chapel is now, a little bit south of that.
between that and either law or prayer year.
And then they'd have, throw these raisins, and then if they had potatoes, or they'd save their potatoes, ice potatoes, take them over to the, I don't,
and get to throwing those at each other.
And it was pretty slimy to get out of there.
The floors got pretty thick.
You mentioned prune races.
Could you describe what a prune race was?
It was merely, I guess, sophomores, particularly those who didn't care for prunes, but saved them.
or the upperclassmen in general, and then they'd pick out some of the fish and see who could eat the most prunes in the shortest time.
What happened to the loser?
I don't recall that.

How would you, you know, if you were going to kind of give a general summation to the food in the mess hall, well, let's see, the motels are, and the tour books describe them as one, two, three, and four stars.
On up, you know, four stars would be top quality.
How would you rate the food overall?
I thought it did all of us good, but they didn't have the variety they do now.
I think the menu has improved immensely since those days, but I never did see too much wrong.
I still think the mess hall makes the best fruit pies I ever ate.
I imagine the lack of variety in a mess hall was not at all unusual, though.
Well, it cooked in large quantities.
It didn't taste like it did at home.
But I didn't think it particularly bad.
What I was about to say is I would imagine that even at home you didn't get a whole lot of variety either.
Probably not.
I mean, you got vegetables in season, probably did some home canning, but it was probably not the variety of stuff that there is in the general public today.
You mentioned the movies in the Air Dome.
How frequently were they held?
Saturday night, I'm sure.
It seems to me that they had one during the week also.
Did you have to pay for those or were they free?
No, they cost us, I don't know, 10 or 15 cents.
Quite reasonable.
What other types of things did you do for recreation and entertainment?
Well, there was always a game going on.
Handball or...
Of course, there weren't many tennis courts then, but playing football, basketball, and of course had company, or battalion football.
The attendance was very good on those battalion games.
In fact, I enjoyed battalion games as well.
I did the varsity games.
I had some indication from somebody that, what, I believe Bible was coached when you were here?
Yes.
That he attended those quite regularly and picked out a few football players.
That's right.
From those.
I guess at that point there was not the terrific amount of scouting and recruiting that we have today, so he pretty much had to pick his team from...
those who showed up for practice, and then if he could pick a few others out from the... Was it called intramural then, or was it... No, I don't think it was called intramural.
They called it battalion.
Battalion football, battalion basketball, and battalion cross-country.
About walking...
Plenty of places to walk around here.
What about swimming?
No, the only swimming pool that I know of was in the YMCA, in the basement of the YMCA.
Eventually it was covered over and I've forgotten what, I think they made offices over there.
Was Casey's confectionery still there when you were a student?
Oh, yes.
It was going strong.
In fact, I think it had been there, I don't know when that was organized, a year or two before, but I think Bill Sparks was in the class of 18, I believe.
I'm not sure.
Now, was he the one who operated there?
He and Casey both.
In fact,
Mr.
Lavender, who operated the YMCA barbershop, I think sold his share in that for $1 to Bill Sparks.
And I think Bill had that, or Mr.
Lavender had that framed.
But Bill and Casey were pretty good partners.
Did students go to Bryan very much?
By trolley or walk.
They frequently go to Bryan on Saturday afternoon to a picture show or just to be going somewhere and they had a trailer, an open trailer to the
to the streetcar.
The streetcar, they were hanging from the streetcar, and they put the trailer on.
And over about halfway between here and Bryan, coming back, why, somebody from the upper car would unhook it.
And sometimes, a little while before the skipper,
would realize he didn't have the load he was supposed to.
He'd back up and pick us up.
But it reminded me, the cable cars in San Francisco, the way they hang on to that reminded me of the way they did the old streetcar, and the trailer particularly.
It had a roof but open sides.
Did they have the trailer just on like Saturdays when they were expecting the big crowd?
In larger crowds, yes.
Otherwise it ran on the hour and I remember Joe Howell, who was registrar here for many years preceded Mr. Heaton and then was president of John Tarleton, sold tickets.
right between, right outside of Speza Hall.
Now was there actually a station there?
Or did they just have a little stand from which they sold tickets?
Joe hawked them.
He just walked up down the street selling tickets.
Calling out tickets for the trolley.
So the train, the trolley just came onto campus and stopped?
Stopped just about where, between Speza
